  "prompt": "How much money did each candidate spend in the 1912 election?",
  "response": "The 1912 U.S. presidential election was a historic and contentious race involving four major candidates: **William Howard Taft** (Republican), **Woodrow Wilson** (Democrat), **Theodore Roosevelt** (Progressive/Bull Moose Party), and **Eugene V. Debs** (Socialist). Campaign spending in this era was far lower than in modern elections, but exact figures are difficult to determine due to limited record-keeping at the time. Here are approximate estimates of how much each candidate spent:\n\n1. **Woodrow Wilson (Democrat)**  \n   Wilson's campaign spent around **$1.1 million**, which was considered moderate for the time. His campaign focused on progressive reforms and limited spending compared to his opponents.\n\n2. **Theodore Roosevelt (Progressive/Bull Moose Party)**  \n   Roosevelt's campaign was the most expensive, estimated at **$1.6 million**. The newly formed Progressive Party raised significant funds from wealthy donors to support his candidacy.\n\n3. **William Howard Taft (Republican)**  \n   Taft's campaign spent approximately **$800,000**. His fundraising efforts were hampered by internal divisions within the Republican Party, as many Republicans supported Roosevelt instead.\n\n4. **Eugene V. Debs (Socialist)**  \n   Debs' campaign was the least expensive, spending only around **$66,000**. The Socialist Party relied on small donations from working-class supporters and did not have the same financial resources as the other candidates.\n\nFor context, campaign spending in 1912 was much lower than in modern elections, and much of the funds went toward printed materials, rallies, and travel. Woodrow Wilson ultimately won the election, benefiting from the split in the Republican vote between Taft and Roosevelt.",
